    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-02-27T16:34:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-02-27T16:34:00-05:00" n="168"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d168">
                <head>168. Telegram 563 From the Embassy in Costa Rica to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d168fn1">Source: National Archives,
                        Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box
                        779, Country Files, Latin America, Costa Rica. Confidential.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d168fn2">The Embassy reported that the
                        Government of Costa Rican had received an offer from the Soviet Union to
                        rehabilitate two major ports, financed through loans repayable with coffee
                        exports to the Soviet Union.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San Jose</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-02-27T21:34:00+00:00">February 27, 1969, 2134Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d168-1" n="1" xml:id="pg_d168-1"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Soviet Offer of US Assistance to <gloss target="#GOCR1">GOCR</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Planning Minister Rodriguez told <gloss target="#USAID1">USAID</gloss> Director
                    today that Soviet Government has within last few days offered to
                    build/rehabilitate Limon and Puntarenas ports. Projects would be financed in
                    form of loan repayable by Costa Rican coffee exports to USSR, with coffee priced
                    at traditional market levels. Rodriguez implied that proposal was under study by
                    GOCR.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Boonstra</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
